  "prompt": "According to the first law of motion, external force stops a body in uniform motion. What force do I have if I stop a rolling pin.?",
  "response": "When you stop a rolling pin, you are applying an external force to it, which is in accordance with Newton's first law of motion. This law states that an object in uniform motion will remain in that state of motion unless acted upon by an external force. \n\nIn this case, when you stop the rolling pin, you exert a force opposite to the direction of its motion (often friction and push from your hand). This force counteracts its inertia (the tendency of the rolling pin to keep moving due to its mass). Once your external force is greater than the rolling pin's inertia, it will decelerate and eventually stop. \n\nTo summarize, the force you apply to stop the rolling pin can be considered an external force that changes its state from motion to rest.",
